{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "translator-2",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Use \"above-the-phenomenal\" once in this sentence + expand TN2",
    "content": "1. **Yes, it is a significant problem for this specific sentence.** The sentence's rhetorical force depends entirely on the reader seeing that 形而上 *contains* 形 -- that the \"metaphysical\" literally means \"above the phenomenal,\" so when the author says \"the Way is 形而上 and ritual conduct is 形,\" the reader sees a single axis with ritual conduct at the bottom (形/phenomenal) and the Way at the top (形而上/above-the-phenomenal). In English, \"the metaphysical\" and \"the phenomenal\" appear to be two unrelated terms. The vertical structure collapses.\n\n2. **We already have a TN for this** -- TN2 in the draft explains the author's reinterpretation of 形 as 现象. But it does not make the *embedded structure* visible. A TN can explain it, but the reader still will not *see* it in the English sentence the way the Chinese reader sees it in 形/形而上.\n\n3. **For this one sentence, use a hyphenated compound inline, then revert.** Render the sentence as:\n\n\"Thus the Way is the highest -- it is *above-the-phenomenal* (形而上) -- while ritual conduct is the lowest -- it is *the phenomenal* (形) itself.\"\n\nThen add to TN2 (which already exists): \"The Chinese term 形而上 (the metaphysical) literally means 'above form/the phenomenal' (形 + 而上). In this sentence, the author exploits this internal structure: ritual conduct sits at the level of 形 (the phenomenal), while the Way sits at the level of 形而上 (above the phenomenal). We render this sentence with 'above-the-phenomenal' to make this vertical relationship visible.\"\n\nAfter this sentence, revert to \"the metaphysical\" for all subsequent occurrences. The hyphenated form is a one-time device to make the architecture visible at the moment it matters. It is not a competing translation -- it is a window into the Chinese that opens once and closes."
  }
}
